  • Highly specific for occlusion of the left anterior descending artery.
  • Very similar ECG changes to STEMI but changes are only transient.
  • Characteristics of the pain are indistinguishable from ischemic angina. Even autonomic symptoms are present. It is also relieved by nitrates. (However response is more rapid than thrombotic ischemia)
  • Spasm may be so severe that patient even develops arrhythmias / cardiac arrest.
    • Angina occurs at rest and particularly from midnight to early morning.
    • Effort and exercise tolerance are preserved but spasm can be triggered by exercise during 'hot phase' of the condition.
      • Other triggers: recreational drugs and alcohol, Exposure to extreme cold, allergic reactions, magnesium deficiency.
    • Episodes can appear in clusters
  • Beta blockers are contraindicated as they can worse spasm.
  • Management is with dihydropyridine calcium channel blocker (felodipine, amlodipine)
  • Many drugs: Amiodarone, may antibiotics, Metoclopramide, ondansetron, fluconazole, haloperidol

Immunomodulatory drugs


Steroids Calcineurin inhibitors
Glucocorticoids Tacrolimus
Cyclosporine

Glucocorticoids

  • Reduce the size and lymphoid content of lymph nodes and spleen.
  • but no toxic effect on myeloid or erythroid precursors
  • Cell mediated immunity is affected more than humoral immunity.
  • but antibody production is also reduced.
  • Continous administration increases the rate of IgG catabolism.
  • Used for diverse indications including immunosuppresion in organ transplant recipients. (solid organ and haematopoietic)
    Cyclophosphamide
  • DNA alkylating agent
  • Prevents protein synthesis -> anti mitotic activity.
  • Also has immunomodulatory effects. (selective for T cells)
  • Main indications are chemotherapy for haematologic malignancies (lymphomas, multiple myeloma), refractory nephrotic syndrome in children.
  • Solid organ cancers : breast cancer, disseminated neurobalstoma, retinoblastoma.
  • Side effects: haemorrhagic cystitis

Azathioprine


cyclosporine

  • Used in organ transplantation (kidney, pancreas, liver, heart), treatment of GVHD, and autoimmune diseases.
  • cyclosporine + MTX combination is standard treatment to prevent GVHD after allogenic stem cell transplantation.
  • Also used in rheumatoid arthritis, psoriasis.
  • Blocks activation of T cells
  • mechanism: Binds intracellular cyclophillin (a type of immunophillin) and the complex inhibits cytoplasmic phosphatase called calcineurin. Inhibition of calcineurin inhibits secretion of IL-2, IL-3 and IFN-gamma on antigen stimulated T cells.
  • It is a P450 substrate. -> requires individual dosage adjustments for patients
  • Side effects:
    • nephrotoxic, hyperkalemia,
    • seizures + altered mental status,
    • hirsiutism,
    • hypertension, hyperglycaemia
    • hyperplasia of gums (gingival)
    • Mnemonic: All Hs - hyperkalemia, (and kidney injury), hairy - hirsiutism, hyperglycemia, hypertension, hyperplasia of gums, "hysteria" - altered mental status
  • Tacrolimus is a similar agent with used for the same indications. However, it binds to immunophillin-FK-binding protein rather than cyclophillin.

Pseudomonas species normally inhabit soil, water, and vegetation and can be isolated from the skin, throat, and stool of healthy persons. They often colonize hospital food, sinks, taps, mops, and respiratory equipment. Spread is from patient to patient via contact with fomites or by ingestion of contaminated food and water.

  • Streptococcus pneumoniae: Rust-colored sputum
  • Pseudomonas, Haemophilus and pneumococcal (streptococcal) species: May produce green sputum
  • Klebsiella species pneumonia: Red currant-jelly sputum (mnemonic: kurrant)

[!TIP] Summary
Young patient with recurrent sinopulmonary infection, occular telangiectasia, cerebellar ataxia, and extrapyramidal motor function. They have increased risk of malignancy.

  • There is a mutation in the ATM gene.

[!INFO] This gene is necessary for the action of tumour suppressors p53 and BRCA1.

  • Classic AT usually presents either at birth, with partial combined immunodeficiency, or in early childhood, when neurologic abnormalities begin.
  • Immunodeficiency (there is reduced number of T cells) is most commonly manifested by recurrent sinopulmonary infections.
  • Progressive pulmonary disease and hematologic malignancy are major causes of morbidity and mortality

Pathogenesis

Pathogenesis : point mutation in beta globin gene. Thymine for adenine causes valine for glutamic acid. This produces "HbS".
Inheritance is #autosomal-Recessive
Full blood count

  • Sickle cell disease patients have significant reticulocytosis.
    • Reduction in reticulocyte count is beneficial as reticulocytes are 'sticky' and promote vasoocclusion.
  • Granulocytosis is common and fluctuating in course.
  • HbS has a lower affinity for oxygen than HbA.
  • The Deoxygenated form of HbS polymerises insolubly.
  • Cells progressively become rigid and irreversibly sicked due to intracellular dehytration and potassium loss.
  • Symptoms begin at 6 months of age when Hb syntheis switches from HbF to HbA.

Inheritance and phenotypes:

  • HbAS (HbA gene + HbS gene) -> Asymptomatic carriers.

    • Offers protection against Falciparum malaria.
    • Mechanism: falciparum infected cells sickle more rapidly and are removed by the spleen more quickly.Source

  • low temperature, acidosis, hypoxia, dehyration and infection and excessive exercise.

  • Painful vasoocclusive crisis is the commonest clinical manifestation.

  1. Acute chest syndrome:
    1. Presents with chest pain, tachypnoea, fever, cough and desaturation.
    2. Infection, pulmonary infarction from vaso-occlusion or [[2020-NOV-BasicSciences#Fat embolism|Fat embolism]] from necrotic bone. (chest pain with fever, SOB, hypoxia, with new CXR changes) (Mx is with oxygen antibiotics and exchange transfusion if poor response to initial measures).
    3. Not necessarily caused by sequestion
  2. The spleen in Sickle cell disease:
    • Splenomegaly is found during the first decade of life, but later it undergoes atrophy progressively due to repeated vaso-occlusive attacks, ultimately leading to autosplenectomy. (spleen becomes fibrotic)Source
    • Harrison's: Spleen loses function between 18 to 36 months of life.
  3. Aplastic crisis:
    • Acute drop in Hb with reduced reticulocytes (whereas normally HbS patients have high retic counts).
    • This is due to "cessation of erythroid activity"
    • This virus infects RBC progenitors in bone marrow resulting in impaired cell division for a few days.
    • Usually aplastic crisis is self limited and erythyropoiesis recovers in about a week.
    • End organ effects: renal papillary necrosis, retinal occlusion and detachment,
  • Bone: Avascular necrosis of hips and shoulders, osteomyelitis with staph, strep and salmonella.
  • Renal: chronic tubulointerstitial nephritis and renal papillary necrosis. (renal failure is common in adults)
  • Functional asplenia occurs in all
  1. Niconrandil: Potassium channel activator (K-ATP channel).
    3. Potassium channel activators dilate arterial smooth muscle.
    4. Nicorandil has nitrate groups as well so it also dilates veins.
    5. So arterial and venodilation exerts an antianginal effect.
    6. Side effects: headache

Usually asymptomatic. -

  • Antimitochondrial antibodies are found in all patients. M2 is specific for PBC. (M2 is against the E2 subunit of pyruvate dehydrogenase complex)
    • (passmedicine - 30% can have anti smooth muscle antibodies)
  • IgM is also elevated. Source
  • Presentation: Asymptomatic with #hepatomegaly and raised ALP. (raised ALP is often the only abnormal investigation)
  • Pruritus and fatigue.
  • Raised cholesterol and Xanthelasma - hypercholesterolemia.
  • Conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia late feature Source
    • Dense lymphocytic infiltrate in portal tracts with granulomatous destruction and loss of medium sized interlobular bile ducts.
    • florid duct lesion is pathognomonic. Source
    • Change are patchy within the liver and they can be missed on biopsy.
      Management
      Ursodeoxycholic acid -> improves prognosis.

Histoplasmosis

Caused by fungus; histoplasma capsulatum.
Mycelium is the infective stage.
Found in soil nourished with bird dropping.
Disturbance of soil leads to aerosolization of microconidia which then infect humans upon inhalation.
Exposures increasing risk : spelunking, logging, demolition of old building.
They are engulved by marcophages; Inside macrophages, the hyphae become the yeast form.
Using the macrophages, the disseminate to the mediastinal lymph nodes and the rest of the reticuloendothelial system.
In immunocompetent hosts, infection is mild or asymptomatic. The immune system develops cell mediated immunity and arrests spread of the fungus by forming granulomas which calcify. (calfied lesions are seen in healthy people from endemic areas.)

In immunocompromised patients, disseminated infection can occur.
Illness can range from mild to life threatening.
Diagnosis: histoplasma antigen test.
Treatment: mild cases - itraconazole; others - liposomal amphotericin B.
